      "description": "The algorithm iterates over all currently active trains for each day, resulting in O(m·a) time where a is the number of active trains. In the worst case (e.g., n = m = 200 000 and many trains stay active for many days) this leads to ~4·10^10 operations and will exceed time limits.",
      "triggering_input": "n = 200000, m = 200000\nAll x_i = 1, y_i = 1\nFirst 100000 operations are op=1 (add) for distinct models, next 100000 operations are op=2 (remove) for the same models.\nThe program will loop over up to 100000 active trains for each of the remaining 100000 days, causing ~10^10 iterations.",
      "fix": "Replace the per‑day full scan with a sqrt‑decomposition / bucket solution.\n- Choose a threshold B ≈ √(2·10^5) (e.g., 450).\n- For every train with period c = x_i + y_i ≤ B, keep a 2‑D array small[c][offset] that stores how many active trains of that period are currently in the maintenance part for each offset (0‑based). When a train is added, increment small[c][offset] for all offsets where it would be in maintenance (i.e., offsets x_i … c‑1). When it is removed, decrement the same entries. The answer for a day is then the sum over all c ≤ B of small[c][day % c].\n- For trains with period c > B, the number of maintenance intervals they generate within the whole timeline is at most m / c ≤ B. For such a train we can schedule its maintenance intervals using a difference array diff[day] (range add +1 on each maintenance interval). When the train is added we compute its first maintenance interval [start, end] and push future intervals by jumping c days each time, updating diff via a Fenwick tree or a simple array of length m+2. When the train is removed we undo the same updates.\n- Finally, after processing the operation of the day, the answer is diff_prefix[day] + sum_{c≤B} small[c][day % c].\nThis yields O((n+m)·√m) time and O(m) memory, which fits the constraints.",
      "confirmed": true,
      "reasoning": "The original code is logically correct for small inputs but its per‑day full scan makes it infeasible for the maximal constraints. The described bucket approach eliminates the inner loop over active trains, guaranteeing the required performance while preserving the correct counting logic."
